TI  - Surgical treatment for duodenal involvement in Crohn's disease: report of a case.
PG  - 858-62
AB  - A 29-year-old woman was hospitalized with a 1-month history of postprandial
      epigastric pain, nausea, and vomiting. An upper gastrointestinal tract X-ray
      series showed a marked narrowing of the pyloric region. A histological
      examination of duodenal mucosal biopsy samples showed granulomatous inflammation,
      and thus a diagnosis of intrinsic duodenal Crohn's disease was made. A second
      upper gastrointestinal tract X-ray revealed a persistent gastric outlet
      obstruction. At laparotomy, the duodenal wall was found to be thickened over a
      distance measuring 3.5 cm in length from the pyloric ring. A longitudinal
      incision was made over the entire length, up to 5.5 cm beyond the pyloric ring on
      either side, while Finney-type anastomosis was also performed. A postoperative
      upper gastrointestinal tract X-ray showed an improvement in the gastroduodenal
      passage. Enteral nutrition therapy was provided postoperatively. Omeprazole was
      administered at a dose of 20 mg/day for 2 months. The patient currently remains
      on maintenance therapy with famotidine at 20 mg/day and is clinically doing well.
